## Pattern 4 — Singleton 

### Category
Creational Pattern

### Intent
Ensure a class has only one instance and provide a global point of access to it.

### Problem it Solves
The UNO deck must be shared by all players. If multiple `Deck` objects could be created, players might draw from different decks — breaking the game entirely.

### Solution
`Deck` has a **private constructor** and a **static `getInstance()` method** that always returns the same object.

```java
// Deck.java
public class Deck {
    private static Deck instance;  // the one and only instance

    private Deck() {               // private → cannot call new Deck()
        drawPile = new LinkedList<>(CardFactory.createFullDeck());
        discardPile = new LinkedList<>();
    }

    public static Deck getInstance() {
        if (instance == null) {
            instance = new Deck();  // created only once
        }
        return instance;
    }

    public static void reset() {   // start a fresh game
        instance = new Deck();
    }
}
```

### Proof it Works
```java
Deck d1 = Deck.getInstance();
Deck d2 = Deck.getInstance();
System.out.println(d1 == d2); // true — same object!
```

### Roles
| Role | Class |
|------|-------|
| Singleton | `Deck` |

### Benefit
Every call to `Deck.getInstance()` anywhere in the project returns the exact same deck. No accidental duplication possible.
